===Verb===
{{en-verb|write<,,wrote,written> off}}

# {{lb|en|accounting|transitive}} To [[reduce]] the [[book value]] of (an [[asset]]) to [[zero]].
# {{lb|en|accounting|transitive}} To record (an [[expenditure]]) as an expense.
# {{lb|en|accounting|transitive}} To [[remove]] a portion of a [[debt]] or an amount of an [[account]] owed, counting it as a loss (as a [[gesture]] of [[goodwill]] for example).
# {{lb|en|accounting}} To record a [[notional]] expense such as [[amortization]] or [[depreciation]].
# To treat as a {{m|en|write-off}}, a {{m|en|total loss}}, especially something damaged beyond economic repair.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2020 May 20|title=Fleet News: Collision-damaged '800' at Wolverton|journal=Rail|page=25|text=The '800' received substantial collision damage, while the High Speed Train power car was '''written off'''.}}
# {{lb|en|figurative|transitive}} To assign a low value to (something).
#: {{ux|en|When Katya was injured, he '''wrote off''' the team's chances in the finals.}}
#* '''2015''', Daniel Taylor, ''Manchester City’s Sergio Agüero too good for Chelsea as Diego Costa labours'' (in ''The Guardian'', 16 August 2015)[http://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/aug/16/manchester-city-chelsea-premier-league-match-report]
#*: They have shown their staying power before and it would be daft to '''write them off''' but it must be disturbing, nonetheless, for Mourinho that his team are five points behind already and locked in a game of catch-up against the side that has just subjected them to a rare, old-fashioned beating.

